00:00:21.610 --> 00:00:24.360
PROFESSOR: I'm very
interested in teaching in ways

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:26.420
that really help you learn.

00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:33.640
And one of the most
difficult things to learn

00:00:33.640 --> 00:00:37.960
is when you have to unlearn
something you believe.

00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:40.250
So if you have learned
a concept wrong

00:00:40.250 --> 00:00:43.630
in your previous
education and learnings,

00:00:43.630 --> 00:00:46.973
your mind is really
reluctant to let go of it.

00:00:46.973 --> 00:00:47.960
OK?

00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:52.140
And I have a wife who is a
middle school science teacher.

00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:53.860
She also has a PhD in biology.

00:00:53.860 --> 00:00:56.750
But she really studies
to understand kids

00:00:56.750 --> 00:00:58.050
and how they learn.

00:00:58.050 --> 00:01:00.500
And MIT students aren't much
different from 6th graders,

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:02.541
to tell you the truth,
when it comes to learning.

00:01:02.541 --> 00:01:04.144
None of us are.

00:01:04.144 --> 00:01:05.935
But they're just a
little more transparent.

00:01:09.558 --> 00:01:13.430
What you can do to help a
person unlearn something they've

00:01:13.430 --> 00:01:15.960
learned wrong, the
best time is when

00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:18.980
you run into something
called a "discrepant event."

00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:20.685
So when you think
you know the answer,

00:01:20.685 --> 00:01:23.850
and I'm asking you these
questions, and you're wrong,

00:01:23.850 --> 00:01:25.730
really try to figure
out what it is

00:01:25.730 --> 00:01:28.250
you believe that
led you to that,

00:01:28.250 --> 00:01:31.372
and see if you can undo that
in getting to the answer.

00:01:31.372 --> 00:01:32.830
So some of these
concept questions,

00:01:32.830 --> 00:01:34.440
if you'd like to talk
about them further,

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:36.800
I think they're great for
discussions in your recitation

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:37.300
section.

00:01:37.300 --> 00:01:38.940
Look at Professor Gossard here.

00:01:38.940 --> 00:01:41.620
So talk about these
things, and really try

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:44.690
to get to the bottom
of why you perhaps

00:01:44.690 --> 00:01:49.040
had a concept that wasn't
quite up to what you needed.

00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:50.080
OK.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:53.670
We're going to move on.

00:01:53.670 --> 00:01:54.910
OK.

00:01:54.910 --> 00:01:57.850
Now we're going to get on
to talking about velocities

00:01:57.850 --> 00:01:59.290
in rotating frames.

00:01:59.290 --> 00:02:02.690
And by velocities, I
also mean derivatives

00:02:02.690 --> 00:02:04.320
of vectors in rotating frames.

00:02:22.230 --> 00:02:24.800
Just to give you a quick
reminder of where we started

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:27.900
this conversation,
this is concept

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:36.320
if you have three points-- A,
B, and O in this fixed frame.

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:44.240
This is r A with respect
to O, B with respect to A,

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:47.550
and B with respect
to O, all vectors.

00:02:47.550 --> 00:02:49.900
And we're interested
in computing

00:02:49.900 --> 00:02:54.150
the velocities of,
say, point B. So we

00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:57.880
were talking about the
derivative with respect

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:01.650
to time of this vector.

00:03:01.650 --> 00:03:06.360
And we can make it up as a sum
of the derivatives with respect

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:07.930
to time of these
other two vectors.

00:03:19.420 --> 00:03:21.370
But now there's a
really important point.

00:03:21.370 --> 00:03:22.870
When you're taking
time derivatives,

00:03:22.870 --> 00:03:26.450
you have to be
explicit about what

00:03:26.450 --> 00:03:28.765
it's with respect to--
what frame of reference

00:03:28.765 --> 00:03:29.640
you're talking about.

00:03:29.640 --> 00:03:33.580
In this case we want to know
the velocity with respect

00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:35.110
to this reference frame.

00:03:35.110 --> 00:03:37.520
So both of these
derivatives have

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:40.640
to be taken with
respect to that frame.

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:42.780
Well this one's easy.

00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:46.000
This is purely translational.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.980
It has nothing to do
with rotations, or won't.

00:03:48.980 --> 00:03:53.910
We're going to think in terms
of having an object out here.

00:03:53.910 --> 00:03:58.320
So maybe a rigid body to which
we have attached a rotating

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:02.660
frame at A. And I'll call
this the rotating reference

00:04:02.660 --> 00:04:05.200
frame A x prime y prime.

00:04:05.200 --> 00:04:06.260
And it might be rotating.

00:04:06.260 --> 00:04:10.000
But this point is just the
point with which we describe

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:11.520
the translation of the body.

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:13.150
So this one's pretty easy.

00:04:13.150 --> 00:04:16.029
This one's just the velocity
of A with respect to O.

00:04:16.029 --> 00:04:21.800
But this one has complications.

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:24.210
And I'm going to do it first,
the answer to this, just

00:04:24.210 --> 00:04:27.110
intuitively-- appeal
to your intuition

00:04:27.110 --> 00:04:29.710
about why this should be.

00:04:29.710 --> 00:04:33.910
So this is my merry-go-round.

00:04:33.910 --> 00:04:36.180
And I've set up my
little coordinate system.

00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:39.200
This is my A, x prime y
prime coordinate system.

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:43.000
I've stuck my dog
here on the x-axis.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:49.280
And if he's running
some direction,

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:53.550
he has a velocity with respect
to this reference frame.

00:04:53.550 --> 00:04:56.210
If you're here at A, watch
it, and you'll see him moving.

00:04:56.210 --> 00:04:59.400
And it will have nothing
to do with the rotation.

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:01.410
You will just see
the dog moving.

00:05:01.410 --> 00:05:05.260
And if this is rotating, and
you're sitting there rotating

00:05:05.260 --> 00:05:09.650
with it watching the dog, does
the motion of the dog change?

00:05:09.650 --> 00:05:11.670
You just see it just
the same way, right?

00:05:11.670 --> 00:05:12.260
OK.

00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:16.340
So there's one part of the
motion of the dog that's

00:05:16.340 --> 00:05:18.340
with respect to
this frame that has

00:05:18.340 --> 00:05:20.540
nothing to do with rotation.

00:05:20.540 --> 00:05:21.250
OK.

00:05:21.250 --> 00:05:27.050
So now let's say in an outside,
and from an outside point

00:05:27.050 --> 00:05:31.800
of view, if we
measure the velocity

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:34.620
of the dog with respect
to point A-- that's

00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:39.250
the one you can see-- and
to observer outside says

00:05:39.250 --> 00:05:42.580
what's the velocity of
dog with respect to A,

00:05:42.580 --> 00:05:48.275
will the answer differ
if there's rotation?

00:05:52.190 --> 00:05:53.360
OK.

00:05:53.360 --> 00:05:55.590
Now, what we're
going to find out

00:05:55.590 --> 00:05:58.580
is that there's actually
two contributions.

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:01.840
So the dog running with
respect to this merry-go-round

00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:04.930
is one contribution
to the velocity.

00:06:04.930 --> 00:06:07.410
There's another contribution
that comes from the fact

00:06:07.410 --> 00:06:09.700
that you're sitting
out there watching,

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:12.180
and you see definitely the dog
move when the thing rotates,

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:12.880
right?

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:13.380
OK.

00:06:13.380 --> 00:06:16.880
And if we only do that,
if the only rotation--

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:19.430
and we'll do a case where
the dog's not running, just

00:06:19.430 --> 00:06:21.280
sitting still--
what's the velocity

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:24.165
of the dog with respect to
point A due to the rotation?

00:06:27.990 --> 00:06:30.820
I mean you've done lots
of problems like this.

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:32.470
This is just pure
rotation problem.

00:06:32.470 --> 00:06:35.980
You know the angular
rate-- theta dot, or omega.

00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:39.300
What's the velocity of
point B if point A is fixed

00:06:39.300 --> 00:06:41.730
and this thing rotates?

00:06:41.730 --> 00:06:42.780
r omega.

00:06:42.780 --> 00:06:43.900
You all know that.

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:44.840
OK.

00:06:44.840 --> 00:06:50.540
And then we'll call the velocity
of the dog relative to point

00:06:50.540 --> 00:06:54.280
A due to the fact that he
is moving in this frame,

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:58.040
we'll call that
velocity to the dog.

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:01.520
From the point of view of in the
frame is a different quantity.

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:04.622
They're both vectors, and
you can add them together.

00:07:04.622 --> 00:07:06.205
So in fact the
answer-- I'm just going

00:07:06.205 --> 00:07:09.720
to give you the answer to this
problem-- the answer to this

00:07:09.720 --> 00:07:14.860
is the velocity of
A with respect to O

00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:24.010
plus the derivative of r B/A
with respect to time as seen

00:07:24.010 --> 00:07:29.660
from within the A
xyz prime frame,

00:07:29.660 --> 00:07:32.710
plus a term here
due to rotation.

00:07:35.540 --> 00:07:41.640
And we know that the magnitude
of this answer is some r omega.

00:07:41.640 --> 00:07:43.045
We know it looks like r omega.

00:07:45.890 --> 00:07:48.760
So to interpret this as
meaning the derivative

00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:55.500
of this vector-- this thing--
as if you were in the frame.

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:57.450
And that accounts
for the dog running.

00:07:57.450 --> 00:07:58.850
This is just the dog running.

00:08:05.350 --> 00:08:09.360
And mathematically, I
actually find it easier

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:12.310
to say what this
piece means is this

00:08:12.310 --> 00:08:15.180
is the velocity of
the dog with respect

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:20.960
to A with omega equal to 0.

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:21.870
It's the same thing.

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:25.490
This is what you see
if there's no rotation.

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:27.100
That piece.

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:28.980
And this is the
piece with rotation.

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:33.350
But I want you to think
something through here.

00:08:38.500 --> 00:08:39.760
Come on.

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:42.419
I'm still learning
how to do this.

00:08:42.419 --> 00:08:42.919
OK.

00:08:46.830 --> 00:08:49.590
So I have my little
reference frames like this.

00:08:49.590 --> 00:08:53.620
I'm going to rotate it in this
direction, which given xyz

00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:55.570
ought to be in that direction.

00:08:55.570 --> 00:08:57.680
So the rotation rate,
if it's going like this,

00:08:57.680 --> 00:09:00.100
I'm going to give
it a constant value,

00:09:00.100 --> 00:09:05.620
is that the vector omega is some
omega in the k hat direction,

00:09:05.620 --> 00:09:07.270
right?

00:09:07.270 --> 00:09:16.540
And I have on this
body-- here's my wheel,

00:09:16.540 --> 00:09:23.770
and here's B, and here's A.
And this is my little x-axis,

00:09:23.770 --> 00:09:25.230
my x-prime axis.

00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:31.240
And it has associated with it
a lowercase i hat unit vector.

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:32.910
And off in this
direction then would

00:09:32.910 --> 00:09:37.860
be the y prime with
a j hat unit vector.

00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:38.700
OK.

00:09:38.700 --> 00:09:42.340
So what's the vector r B/A?

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:46.290
How would you write it in vector
notation in components here?

00:09:49.750 --> 00:09:54.820
So this is r B/A
from here to here.

00:09:54.820 --> 00:09:57.313
And what's its direction?

00:09:57.313 --> 00:09:59.240
AUDIENCE: i hat?

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:00.249
PROFESSOR: i hat.

00:10:00.249 --> 00:10:01.540
And is it positive or negative?

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:09.110
So this is the vector.

00:10:09.110 --> 00:10:15.210
At some magnitude r B/A in
the positive i hat direction,

00:10:15.210 --> 00:10:17.860
the arrow goes,
when you say r B/A,

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:22.280
this is B with respect to
A, the arrow goes with B.

00:10:22.280 --> 00:10:25.485
So this, it's
positive r B/A i hat.

00:10:25.485 --> 00:10:29.690
And what is the velocity that
we have discovered up here,

00:10:29.690 --> 00:10:32.350
the velocity of B
with respect to A as

00:10:32.350 --> 00:10:35.980
measured inside of A xyz?

00:10:35.980 --> 00:10:39.180
That's this piece here.

00:10:39.180 --> 00:10:41.777
In vector terms?

00:10:41.777 --> 00:10:43.610
And we've figured out
what its velocity was.

00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:45.320
It's some r omega.

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:50.320
The r's r B/A-- the magnitude,
the length of that r.

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:54.040
Clearly got to be this
length right here.

00:10:54.040 --> 00:10:57.800
And the omega is given.

00:10:57.800 --> 00:10:59.180
So what direction?

00:10:59.180 --> 00:11:00.896
You know that the
magnitudes are omega.

00:11:00.896 --> 00:11:01.770
What's the direction?

00:11:07.764 --> 00:11:08.730
AUDIENCE: j hat?

00:11:08.730 --> 00:11:09.438
PROFESSOR: j hat.

00:11:09.438 --> 00:11:10.470
OK.

00:11:10.470 --> 00:11:13.360
So what we're saying
is the velocity

00:11:13.360 --> 00:11:21.160
of B with respect to A as seen
from inside this A frame is

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:31.780
r B/A omega with respect to
O in the j hat direction.

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:35.996
Now this has a k
associated with it.

00:11:35.996 --> 00:11:37.370
That has an i
associated with it.

00:11:37.370 --> 00:11:39.550
And this has a j
associated with it.

00:11:39.550 --> 00:11:43.164
So as a product r omega,
what kind of product is it?

00:11:43.164 --> 00:11:44.330
What you know about vectors?

00:11:44.330 --> 00:11:45.630
What does it have to be?

00:11:45.630 --> 00:11:49.160
Is it a dot product
between omega and r?

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:51.242
Is it a cross product?

00:11:51.242 --> 00:11:52.960
I hear somebody
saying cross product.

00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:53.880
But what's the order?

00:11:53.880 --> 00:11:56.380
So I want you to figure
out-- just deduce

00:11:56.380 --> 00:11:59.230
what the vector
notation is that gets

00:11:59.230 --> 00:12:01.749
you the right velocity--
the correct velocity--

00:12:01.749 --> 00:12:03.415
correct magnitude and
correct direction.

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:11.150
So the answer is
positive r omega j.

00:12:16.070 --> 00:12:17.550
AUDIENCE: Omega cross r?

00:12:17.550 --> 00:12:18.510
PROFESSOR: Omega.

00:12:18.510 --> 00:12:19.850
AUDIENCE: Cross to the r?

00:12:19.850 --> 00:12:20.891
PROFESSOR: Omega cross r.

00:12:20.891 --> 00:12:29.660
So I hear one person, omega
with respect to O cross r B/A.

00:12:29.660 --> 00:12:32.220
And these are now both vectors.

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:33.390
Anybody else?

00:12:33.390 --> 00:12:34.989
So if we just think
about unit vector,

00:12:34.989 --> 00:12:36.030
actually, let's check it.

00:12:36.030 --> 00:12:37.880
This is k hat direction.

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:40.170
This was i hat direction.

00:12:40.170 --> 00:12:44.330
And k cross i is positive j.

00:12:44.330 --> 00:12:45.015
So that works.

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:51.980
So in general-- this is,
in fact, the correct answer

00:12:51.980 --> 00:13:01.370
in general-- is that this term
here is omega with respect

00:13:01.370 --> 00:13:09.260
to O cross r B/A. You're
going to use that a lot.

00:13:09.260 --> 00:13:20.500
So to summarize, then--
while that's coming down,

00:13:20.500 --> 00:13:30.620
the velocity of this dog
in a stationary frame where

00:13:30.620 --> 00:13:35.150
A is stationary for a moment is
entirely due to the rotation,

00:13:35.150 --> 00:13:39.320
and it's omega cross r B/A.
And now if the dog starts

00:13:39.320 --> 00:13:43.470
to run with respect to
this reference frame,

00:13:43.470 --> 00:13:46.520
he has some velocity,
which is the other piece

00:13:46.520 --> 00:13:50.400
is velocity of B with
respect to A as seen from A--

00:13:50.400 --> 00:13:52.610
or as you would compute,
you'd just set momentarily,

00:13:52.610 --> 00:13:54.380
omega equal to zero.

00:13:54.380 --> 00:13:58.840
And finally then, the
total formula for velocity.

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:02.720
So the velocity
of B with respect

00:14:02.720 --> 00:14:07.280
to O-- some point on a
rotating reference frame--

00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:15.696
is the velocity of
the frame plus--

00:14:15.696 --> 00:14:18.330
I won't write it as
a derivative now.

00:14:18.330 --> 00:14:23.610
Plus the velocity
of the point, but as

00:14:23.610 --> 00:14:29.180
seen from the point of view
of somebody in the frame,

00:14:29.180 --> 00:14:37.780
plus omega with respect
to O cross r B/A.

00:14:37.780 --> 00:14:40.000
So this is an important formula.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.370
You're going to use it a lot.

00:14:43.370 --> 00:14:45.640
Couple of subtle points in here.

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:49.490
This one-- this thing from as
seen from inside the frame.

00:14:49.490 --> 00:14:55.870
It's also the partial
derivative of r B/A with respect

00:14:55.870 --> 00:15:00.570
to t when omega with
respect to O equals zero.

00:15:00.570 --> 00:15:04.460
That's another way to say this.

00:15:04.460 --> 00:15:07.980
And this term is
another subtlety.

00:15:07.980 --> 00:15:12.907
I was careful to write
with respect to O. Yes?

00:15:12.907 --> 00:15:17.786
AUDIENCE: To make sure I'm not
confused here on this vector

00:15:17.786 --> 00:15:18.286
right there.

00:15:21.709 --> 00:15:23.665
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:15:23.665 --> 00:15:27.088
AUDIENCE: That leftmost term
is the middle one there?

00:15:27.088 --> 00:15:28.570
Or the right one?

00:15:28.570 --> 00:15:30.810
PROFESSOR: So this was
when we were working

00:15:30.810 --> 00:15:37.710
with just the velocity due
to the motion of the dog

00:15:37.710 --> 00:15:40.490
due to rotation
plus-- actually this

00:15:40.490 --> 00:15:44.066
was rotation-- what did I say?

00:15:44.066 --> 00:15:47.482
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
experiments.

00:15:47.482 --> 00:15:50.166
That the term on the
left is the motion

00:15:50.166 --> 00:15:52.298
that you can see from the frame.

00:15:52.298 --> 00:15:53.923
From the right is
the rotation that you

00:15:53.923 --> 00:15:56.270
don't see in the [INAUDIBLE],
but needs to be [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:56.270 --> 00:15:58.080
PROFESSOR: And I can't remember
how I got to this point.

00:15:58.080 --> 00:15:59.710
But I think I was making
a couple of points,

00:15:59.710 --> 00:16:00.860
and rammed them together.

00:16:00.860 --> 00:16:02.480
So this is the correct.

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:04.690
Don't focus on this.

00:16:04.690 --> 00:16:07.410
This is the summary.

00:16:07.410 --> 00:16:12.380
This thing is now
rotating, and translating,

00:16:12.380 --> 00:16:15.220
and the dog's running.

00:16:15.220 --> 00:16:17.400
And I want you to be
able to write down

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:20.590
the total velocity
of the point B

00:16:20.590 --> 00:16:27.400
as seen from a fixed reference
frame fixed on the ground.

00:16:27.400 --> 00:16:29.600
This is with respect to O.

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:32.400
It has three
terms-- the velocity

00:16:32.400 --> 00:16:40.280
of A, the velocity of the
dog relative to the body

00:16:40.280 --> 00:16:43.180
it's on here, and
finally, the component

00:16:43.180 --> 00:16:45.180
of the velocity--
contribution of the velocity

00:16:45.180 --> 00:16:49.630
that you see that's
due to the rotation.

00:16:49.630 --> 00:16:54.360
Now this turns out to be
a really powerful formula.

00:16:54.360 --> 00:16:55.560
It's a generalization.

00:16:55.560 --> 00:17:03.880
It's a special case of
a very general formula.

00:17:03.880 --> 00:17:07.740
Let me catch up
in my notes here.

00:17:07.740 --> 00:17:11.099
Because the following
statement is true.

00:17:11.099 --> 00:17:35.950
So the time derivative
of any vector

00:17:35.950 --> 00:17:44.080
that's defined in
a rotating frame

00:17:44.080 --> 00:17:51.100
is given by-- and we'll
call it just some vector

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:54.095
A. It might be, for
example, angular momentum.

00:17:54.095 --> 00:17:56.590
In fact we'll use
this formula a lot

00:17:56.590 --> 00:17:58.940
when talking about
angular momentum.

00:17:58.940 --> 00:18:04.825
The time derivative
of this vector A--

00:18:04.825 --> 00:18:09.260
whatever it represents--
position, velocity,

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:17.130
angular momentum-- as seen from
a reference frame xy-- O xyz,

00:18:17.130 --> 00:18:27.850
reference frame O-- is made
up of the derivative of A from

00:18:27.850 --> 00:18:31.316
inside the frame plus--

00:18:42.460 --> 00:18:45.150
So it's the same thing.

00:18:45.150 --> 00:18:49.720
This was the derivative of r
B/A. Has two pieces-- the piece

00:18:49.720 --> 00:18:51.980
that came from the dog
running and the piece that

00:18:51.980 --> 00:18:53.690
comes from rotation.

00:18:53.690 --> 00:18:56.680
Any vector, this piece is true.

00:18:56.680 --> 00:18:58.160
It's the derivative
of the vector

00:18:58.160 --> 00:19:03.590
inside the frame in which it's
defined plus omega with respect

00:19:03.590 --> 00:19:10.510
to the reference frame you want
the derivative in cross A. Very

00:19:10.510 --> 00:19:11.390
powerful formula.

00:19:21.310 --> 00:19:25.090
This now is covered in a
couple of different places

00:19:25.090 --> 00:19:28.140
in the readings, and
in the handout that's

00:19:28.140 --> 00:19:30.560
posted called "Kinematics."

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:32.570
So you should read
by now the portion

00:19:32.570 --> 00:19:34.832
of the kinematics thing,
at least on velocities.

00:19:34.832 --> 00:19:37.060
The second half of
that kinematics handout

00:19:37.060 --> 00:19:38.160
is about acceleration.

00:19:38.160 --> 00:19:39.740
So we're going to
use this formula

00:19:39.740 --> 00:19:41.560
to go from velocity
to acceleration.

00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:43.420
I saw a couple hands up.

00:19:43.420 --> 00:19:44.383
Yes?

00:19:44.383 --> 00:19:47.281
AUDIENCE: So what is the
difference between O sub

00:19:47.281 --> 00:19:49.213
xyz and A sub xyz?

00:19:49.213 --> 00:19:51.050
Where are they [INAUDIBLE]?

00:19:51.050 --> 00:19:51.780
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:19:51.780 --> 00:19:58.410
So this is a
merry-go-round on a train,

00:19:58.410 --> 00:19:59.780
and you're looking down on it.

00:19:59.780 --> 00:20:02.950
And the train can move.

00:20:02.950 --> 00:20:05.550
And we fixed to the
ground, not moving,

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:12.030
a reference frame we call O.
And I want to know in this case

00:20:12.030 --> 00:20:15.280
the velocity of the
dog running around

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:20.650
on this merry-go-round
with respect to O.

00:20:20.650 --> 00:20:24.290
It's the sum of three
vector contributions--

00:20:24.290 --> 00:20:28.710
the velocity of the
train, the velocity

00:20:28.710 --> 00:20:35.990
of the dog with respect to
the merry-go-round-- this

00:20:35.990 --> 00:20:37.115
is velocity of the train.

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:43.150
This is with respect
to the merry-go-round.

00:20:43.150 --> 00:20:46.990
And this is the velocity
that you see out there.

00:20:46.990 --> 00:20:52.620
So you're sitting in O. You
are in this fixed frame.

00:20:52.620 --> 00:20:56.170
Which brings up another
subtle point about velocities

00:20:56.170 --> 00:20:59.890
and inertial frames.

00:20:59.890 --> 00:21:04.540
If you are at any fixed
point in an inertial frame--

00:21:04.540 --> 00:21:06.710
you don't have to be
at O; you can be right

00:21:06.710 --> 00:21:10.980
where you are-- this
term is always the same.

00:21:10.980 --> 00:21:14.900
The velocity of this moving
object relative to the frame

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:17.540
is the same to any
observer in the frame--

00:21:17.540 --> 00:21:20.281
any fixed observer in the frame.

00:21:20.281 --> 00:21:20.780
OK?

00:21:23.290 --> 00:21:24.395
And finally, the u.

00:21:24.395 --> 00:21:27.200
But the u, the part
of the contribution

00:21:27.200 --> 00:21:29.290
to the velocity due to the
rotation of this thing,

00:21:29.290 --> 00:21:30.850
you can see it from
out there, right?

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:31.810
It moves.

00:21:31.810 --> 00:21:35.830
Well, the rotation
contribution is this.

00:21:35.830 --> 00:21:38.370
The dog running around is this.

00:21:38.370 --> 00:21:42.300
And the movement of the
train is the first term.

00:21:42.300 --> 00:21:44.240
OK?

00:21:44.240 --> 00:21:44.780
All right.

00:21:44.780 --> 00:21:47.620
And this is the general
formula for the derivative

00:21:47.620 --> 00:21:54.280
of a vector in a
translating, rotating frame.

00:21:54.280 --> 00:21:54.810
Yeah?

00:21:54.810 --> 00:22:00.605
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] vectors
beyond the [INAUDIBLE] v

00:22:00.605 --> 00:22:02.858
of p with respect
to the [INAUDIBLE].

00:22:02.858 --> 00:22:04.316
PROFESSOR: I'm not
following, here.

00:22:04.316 --> 00:22:07.232
AUDIENCE: Are any
