00:22:07.232 --> 00:22:10.148
for example, or v of B
with respect to A, are they

00:22:10.148 --> 00:22:11.245
all vectors?

00:22:11.245 --> 00:22:12.620
PROFESSOR: These
are all vectors.

00:22:12.620 --> 00:22:15.190
And I've gotten
a little careless

00:22:15.190 --> 00:22:18.340
about drawing my underlines
when I haven't broken them down

00:22:18.340 --> 00:22:19.160
into components.

00:22:19.160 --> 00:22:20.590
This is a vector.

00:22:20.590 --> 00:22:22.400
And we can do
this, because we're

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:26.290
relying on formulas for
the sums of vectors.

00:22:26.290 --> 00:22:28.260
So it's the vector.

00:22:28.260 --> 00:22:31.120
There's a vector describing
the velocity of the train.

00:22:31.120 --> 00:22:34.590
For example, if it's moving in
the capital I hat direction,

00:22:34.590 --> 00:22:36.350
you have to say that.

00:22:36.350 --> 00:22:41.240
And this may
actually be the dog.

00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:45.180
At the moment you catch
him, the frame's like this.

00:22:45.180 --> 00:22:51.070
And let's say he's running
in the y direction.

00:22:51.070 --> 00:22:52.840
His direction at
that instant in time

00:22:52.840 --> 00:22:56.730
is in the lowercase
j hat direction

00:22:56.730 --> 00:22:58.420
relative to this frame, right?

00:22:58.420 --> 00:23:01.610
And that j hat
direction has some angle

00:23:01.610 --> 00:23:04.040
with respect to
this frame, which

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:09.320
if you want to reduce
these velocities down

00:23:09.320 --> 00:23:13.130
to the unit vectors
in the inertial frame,

00:23:13.130 --> 00:23:13.930
you can do that.

00:23:13.930 --> 00:23:15.388
But you're going
to have to account

00:23:15.388 --> 00:23:19.930
for the angles of this reference
frame compared to that one.

00:23:19.930 --> 00:23:22.900
So cosine thetas and sine
thetas and that kind of thing.

00:23:25.740 --> 00:23:34.440
One important point about
this general expression

00:23:34.440 --> 00:23:38.290
for the derivative of a vector
in a rotating frame, which

00:23:38.290 --> 00:23:41.250
therefore applies to this
case, because this is just

00:23:41.250 --> 00:23:44.970
the specific example of
derivative of a position

00:23:44.970 --> 00:23:47.420
vector giving you velocity.

00:23:47.420 --> 00:23:54.130
This term and this
term-- these account

00:23:54.130 --> 00:23:56.190
for the change in
length of the vector.

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:03.100
So just to keep it real,
in terms of velocities,

00:24:03.100 --> 00:24:05.530
you see a velocity
that's due to the fact

00:24:05.530 --> 00:24:09.245
that the velocity vector
itself is changing in length.

00:24:12.660 --> 00:24:15.540
Or in this case, the r
vector is changing in length,

00:24:15.540 --> 00:24:18.670
so the velocity has something
to do with the change in length.

00:24:18.670 --> 00:24:23.190
This term is due only to the
fact that it is rotating.

00:24:23.190 --> 00:24:26.280
If the dog's not running,
is his position vector

00:24:26.280 --> 00:24:28.790
changing in length?

00:24:28.790 --> 00:24:30.220
No.

00:24:30.220 --> 00:24:32.370
So this term here
comes from taking

00:24:32.370 --> 00:24:35.140
this derivative of
the position vector

00:24:35.140 --> 00:24:37.330
within the rotating frame.

00:24:37.330 --> 00:24:40.670
So this accounts for the change
in length of that position

00:24:40.670 --> 00:24:42.570
vector.

00:24:42.570 --> 00:24:44.700
This accounts for the rotation.

00:24:44.700 --> 00:24:50.915
This term is the same as
seen from in any frame.

00:24:50.915 --> 00:24:51.790
This is the subtlety.

00:24:54.900 --> 00:24:59.030
This term, you get the same
answer if you see it from here.

00:24:59.030 --> 00:25:00.870
This velocity,
this contribution.

00:25:00.870 --> 00:25:07.040
The dog's speed with respect
to this frame it's in

00:25:07.040 --> 00:25:09.370
is the same to you out
there in the fixed frame

00:25:09.370 --> 00:25:11.240
as it is to somebody
sitting here

00:25:11.240 --> 00:25:14.460
in the frame moving with him.

00:25:14.460 --> 00:25:15.305
Important point.

00:25:19.110 --> 00:25:21.640
It'll become more important
as you do problems.

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:23.999
You need to remember
that doesn't matter

00:25:23.999 --> 00:25:25.040
where you're calculating.

00:25:25.040 --> 00:25:27.440
You're given the
velocity of the dog

00:25:27.440 --> 00:25:30.960
in this frame, and
little i j k components,

00:25:30.960 --> 00:25:34.810
it is in magnitude exactly
the same velocity as you would

00:25:34.810 --> 00:25:37.784
see it in the fixed frame.

00:25:37.784 --> 00:25:39.950
But then you just have to
account for the right unit

00:25:39.950 --> 00:25:41.190
vectors and so forth.

00:25:41.190 --> 00:25:42.062
Yes.

00:25:42.062 --> 00:25:44.894
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] is
the same as the frame,

00:25:44.894 --> 00:25:47.249
but the direction is changing?

00:25:47.249 --> 00:25:49.540
PROFESSOR: The direction is
the same in any frame also.

00:25:49.540 --> 00:25:52.410
It's just that you have
to decide which unit

00:25:52.410 --> 00:25:54.772
vectors to represent it in.

00:25:54.772 --> 00:25:56.230
And when you're in
this frame, it's

00:25:56.230 --> 00:26:00.495
easiest to represent it
in little i j k, right?

00:26:00.495 --> 00:26:01.870
But if you're in
the fixed frame,

00:26:01.870 --> 00:26:05.450
you may want to actually know
the velocity in the fixed

00:26:05.450 --> 00:26:08.584
frames unit vectors, and there's
just geometric conversions

00:26:08.584 --> 00:26:09.500
that'll give you that.

00:26:09.500 --> 00:26:10.460
Yes.

00:26:10.460 --> 00:26:13.350
AUDIENCE: But if theta is like
a function of time [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:13.350 --> 00:26:15.270
how would you use those?

00:26:15.270 --> 00:26:17.190
Does it just work the same way?

00:26:17.190 --> 00:26:20.320
PROFESSOR: So she says if
theta is a function of time,

00:26:20.320 --> 00:26:24.220
if you were trying to convert--
this dog's running in the y

00:26:24.220 --> 00:26:28.430
direction, which is going in
the master frame over there,

00:26:28.430 --> 00:26:31.410
is going to have a component
in the negative capital I hat

00:26:31.410 --> 00:26:34.480
and positive capital J
hat direction, right?

00:26:34.480 --> 00:26:38.020
And you could break down--
let's say his velocity vector is

00:26:38.020 --> 00:26:42.140
like this-- you could break it
down into a component that's

00:26:42.140 --> 00:26:43.840
parallel to the
ground, and a component

00:26:43.840 --> 00:26:45.470
perpendicular to the ground.

00:26:45.470 --> 00:26:47.630
And those then would be
in that reference frame.

00:26:51.347 --> 00:26:53.430
You've all, I would think,
have done some problems

00:26:53.430 --> 00:26:55.690
using polar coordinates.

00:26:55.690 --> 00:26:59.390
And the conversion between
x and y and r and theta

00:26:59.390 --> 00:27:01.820
is you used cosine
thetas and sine

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:03.400
thetas to compute it, right?

00:27:03.400 --> 00:27:08.700
So read that handout
on kinematics,

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:16.940
because it proves this
formula by doing just that.

00:27:16.940 --> 00:27:18.890
It puts everything
