an equal and opposite reaction.

00:31:56.660 --> 00:32:00.510
And I'm going to draw
a picture for this one.

00:32:00.510 --> 00:32:02.800
So here's a particle.

00:32:02.800 --> 00:32:05.020
Here's another particle.

00:32:05.020 --> 00:32:07.070
This is particle 2.

00:32:07.070 --> 00:32:09.120
Particle 1.

00:32:09.120 --> 00:32:12.070
There's a force on
this particle that's

00:32:12.070 --> 00:32:16.920
the force on 2 due
to the presence of 1.

00:32:16.920 --> 00:32:20.000
They've each got a little
gravity, little attraction

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:20.740
from one another.

00:32:20.740 --> 00:32:27.540
And this one has a force on
particle 1 due to particle 2.

00:32:27.540 --> 00:32:28.230
OK?

00:32:28.230 --> 00:32:29.313
They could be two planets.

00:32:32.590 --> 00:32:38.570
And basically what he said
is that for every action,

00:32:38.570 --> 00:32:41.010
there's an equal and
opposite reaction.

00:32:41.010 --> 00:32:47.210
That means that f 21
equals minus f 12.

00:32:50.120 --> 00:32:53.035
And this is called
the strong form

00:32:53.035 --> 00:33:01.450
of Newton's third law,
which the forces are equal,

00:33:01.450 --> 00:33:04.870
opposite, and collinear.

00:33:08.060 --> 00:33:12.160
They actually point exactly
opposite one another.

00:33:12.160 --> 00:33:14.470
And this is true of
mechanical systems.

00:33:14.470 --> 00:33:19.850
You get some rather
interesting subtleties

00:33:19.850 --> 00:33:21.970
when you get into
electromagnetic fields,

00:33:21.970 --> 00:33:23.897
and charged particles,
and things like that.

00:33:23.897 --> 00:33:25.480
So you have to think
really carefully.

00:33:25.480 --> 00:33:29.250
But for the mechanical
systems, the strong form

00:33:29.250 --> 00:33:32.110
will suit us just fine.

00:33:32.110 --> 00:33:33.339
OK.

00:33:33.339 --> 00:33:34.380
Those are the three laws.

00:33:34.380 --> 00:33:41.540
Newton made one major
condition for those to be true.

00:33:41.540 --> 00:33:45.690
What is the assumption that
must be satisfied for these laws

00:33:45.690 --> 00:33:48.094
to be true?

00:33:48.094 --> 00:33:50.830
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] an
inertial reference frame?

00:33:50.830 --> 00:33:55.190
PROFESSOR: I hear "an inertial
reference frame," right?

00:33:55.190 --> 00:33:57.770
And that's what he assumed.

00:33:57.770 --> 00:34:00.990
You have to be in an inertial
frame for these statements

00:34:00.990 --> 00:34:02.110
to be true.

00:34:02.110 --> 00:34:05.510
So then what I want to spend
a few minutes talking about

00:34:05.510 --> 00:34:09.845
is basically what's
an inertial frame.

00:34:09.845 --> 00:34:11.219
Because that's
going to be really

00:34:11.219 --> 00:34:12.480
important in this subject.

00:34:12.480 --> 00:34:15.639
When you start getting on
things that move and rotate,

00:34:15.639 --> 00:34:18.980
things sometimes
are not inertial.

00:34:18.980 --> 00:34:21.639
So I'm going to ask
you a quick question.

00:34:21.639 --> 00:34:24.090
So a reference frame.

00:34:24.090 --> 00:34:27.771
So we had our fixed frame up
there, sitting on the ground,

00:34:27.771 --> 00:34:28.520
here on the Earth.

00:34:28.520 --> 00:34:32.139
Is the Earth an inertial
reference frame, standing

00:34:32.139 --> 00:34:33.360
here observing things?

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:38.540
I want a show of hands.

00:34:38.540 --> 00:34:39.820
I really want some
participation here.

00:34:39.820 --> 00:34:41.940
How many of you think
Earth's an inertial frame?

00:34:41.940 --> 00:34:42.845
Raise your hand.

00:34:42.845 --> 00:34:44.550
It's true.

00:34:44.550 --> 00:34:47.580
How many think it's not true?

00:34:47.580 --> 00:34:50.000
How many think it depends?

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:52.250
On what?

00:34:52.250 --> 00:34:55.250
AUDIENCE: What you
are focusing on.

00:34:55.250 --> 00:34:57.080
PROFESSOR: What the problem is.

00:34:57.080 --> 00:34:59.740
He says it depends on
what you're focusing on.

00:34:59.740 --> 00:35:04.310
So it really depends on
the sizes of the forces

00:35:04.310 --> 00:35:07.430
and the motion
you're interested in.

00:35:07.430 --> 00:35:10.890
Can you give me an example
in which the Earth cannot be

00:35:10.890 --> 00:35:14.730
assumed to be an inertial frame?

00:35:14.730 --> 00:35:16.240
Practical example?

00:35:16.240 --> 00:35:17.740
AUDIENCE: Oh.

00:35:17.740 --> 00:35:18.890
Not practical.

00:35:18.890 --> 00:35:20.874
PROFESSOR: Impractical.

00:35:20.874 --> 00:35:23.850
AUDIENCE: The rotation
of Earth is slowing?

00:35:23.850 --> 00:35:26.167
The rotation of the
Earth is slowing?

00:35:26.167 --> 00:35:28.000
PROFESSOR: Rotation of
the earth is slowing.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:29.850
That's interesting.

00:35:29.850 --> 00:35:32.900
To account for that, you would
definitely not be able to just

00:35:32.900 --> 00:35:34.370
to assume we're inertial.

00:35:34.370 --> 00:35:37.710
But what's an everyday
example of where,

00:35:37.710 --> 00:35:40.954
if you're trying to solve
a problem in this field,

00:35:40.954 --> 00:35:42.745
you couldn't make this
inertial assumption?

00:35:45.896 --> 00:35:47.820
AUDIENCE: Rotation
of the planets?

00:35:47.820 --> 00:35:49.700
PROFESSOR: Well, no,
for the most part,

00:35:49.700 --> 00:35:50.870
you could get most of it.

00:35:50.870 --> 00:35:52.267
But, yeah.

00:35:52.267 --> 00:35:53.850
AUDIENCE: I think
the weather, really,

00:35:53.850 --> 00:35:56.175
because the wind currents,
or like the ocean

00:35:56.175 --> 00:35:58.970
currents are affected by the
fact that the Earth is round.

00:35:58.970 --> 00:36:00.350
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:36:00.350 --> 00:36:01.800
That's a good one.

00:36:01.800 --> 00:36:05.480
In order to account
for the circulation

00:36:05.480 --> 00:36:07.920
you have to take into
account the Earth's motion.

00:36:07.920 --> 00:36:10.125
Let me give you an example.

00:36:10.125 --> 00:36:10.625
Clocks.

00:36:14.720 --> 00:36:18.200
Pendulum clocks.

00:36:18.200 --> 00:36:19.850
Does the speed of
a clock change?

00:36:19.850 --> 00:36:24.550
Is it different at high
noon from midnight?

00:36:29.691 --> 00:36:30.440
What do you think?

00:36:30.440 --> 00:36:31.930
Yes or no?

00:36:31.930 --> 00:36:34.080
How many think that
the actual speed

00:36:34.080 --> 00:36:35.950
of a clock-- the
length of a second--

00:36:35.950 --> 00:36:38.220
would be different at
noon on the Earth--

00:36:38.220 --> 00:36:40.274
a pendulum clock--
from midnight?

00:36:40.274 --> 00:36:41.690
How many think
that might be true?

00:36:41.690 --> 00:36:42.880
It's different?

00:36:42.880 --> 00:36:45.270
How many don't believe
that it would be true?

00:36:45.270 --> 00:36:47.140
How many just not
raising their hands?

00:36:47.140 --> 00:36:48.190
Come on you guys.

00:36:48.190 --> 00:36:49.130
Let's get with it.

00:36:49.130 --> 00:36:49.629
OK.

00:36:52.600 --> 00:36:55.590
So the effective
acceleration of gravity

00:36:55.590 --> 00:36:58.800
that that pendulum feels
is different at noon

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:01.420
from midnight.

00:37:01.420 --> 00:37:07.590
And one reason is because at
noon the sun's pulling away

00:37:07.590 --> 00:37:09.890
from the surface of the
Earth, and at midnight

00:37:09.890 --> 00:37:12.664
the sun's gravity is pulling
in the same direction

00:37:12.664 --> 00:37:14.080
as toward the
center of the Earth.

00:37:14.080 --> 00:37:15.990
The total effective
gravitational

00:37:15.990 --> 00:37:18.410
pull that the
pendulum field changes

00:37:18.410 --> 00:37:21.489
due to the rotation of
the Earth, what it feels.

00:37:21.489 --> 00:37:23.030
The sum of the forces
on the pendulum

00:37:23.030 --> 00:37:25.200
includes the Earth's gravity
and the sun's gravity.

00:37:25.200 --> 00:37:26.790
And the moon also does this.

00:37:26.790 --> 00:37:29.750
So there's daily
variations in the speed

00:37:29.750 --> 00:37:33.160
of pendulum clocks just
because of the Earth's

00:37:33.160 --> 00:37:35.640
rotation with respect
to the sun and the moon.

00:37:35.640 --> 00:37:36.471
Yeah.

00:37:36.471 --> 00:37:39.560
AUDIENCE: Is that even great
enough to be measurable?

00:37:39.560 --> 00:37:41.890
PROFESSOR: So she says,
"Is that even great enough

00:37:41.890 --> 00:37:42.710
to be measurable?"

00:37:42.710 --> 00:37:44.160
So I have a friend, a
guy named Hugh Hunt.

00:37:44.160 --> 00:37:45.950
He's a professor
that teaches dynamics

00:37:45.950 --> 00:37:47.310
at Cambridge University.

00:37:47.310 --> 00:37:52.010
And he is the keeper of
the Trinity College clock.

00:37:52.010 --> 00:37:53.990
Trinity College is
where Newton was.

00:37:53.990 --> 00:37:56.620
So he took me to his clock
one day up in this tower.

00:37:56.620 --> 00:37:58.580
And it's got about a
two-meter pendulum on it.

00:37:58.580 --> 00:38:00.720
And he has got that
clock to run so

00:38:00.720 --> 00:38:06.260
that it gains no more
than one second per month.

00:38:06.260 --> 00:38:07.910
He's really tuned
it up carefully.

00:38:07.910 --> 00:38:10.630
And the key to being
able to do that

00:38:10.630 --> 00:38:15.672
is to do things on
monthly averages.

00:38:15.672 --> 00:38:18.110
So he's got it tuned
so that over a month

00:38:18.110 --> 00:38:20.540
it just barely gains a tiny bit.

00:38:20.540 --> 00:38:22.370
But if you measure
it very carefully

00:38:22.370 --> 00:38:26.320
over the course of the
day, it has amazingly large

00:38:26.320 --> 00:38:28.320
fluctuations.

00:38:28.320 --> 00:38:30.830
One of them is due to the
thing I just described.

00:38:30.830 --> 00:38:34.460
So if you're really trying to
keep close time, it matters.

00:38:34.460 --> 00:38:34.960
OK.

00:38:34.960 --> 00:38:37.176
Another one is gunnery.

00:38:37.176 --> 00:38:38.670
You're shooting long range.

00:38:38.670 --> 00:38:39.920
You're trying to hit a target.

00:38:39.920 --> 00:38:41.750
The fact that the
earth rotates, you

00:38:41.750 --> 00:38:44.640
will not hit the
target if you don't

00:38:44.640 --> 00:38:48.545
account for the effects that are
caused by the Earth's rotation.

00:38:48.545 --> 00:38:49.920
And it's one of
the first reasons

00:38:49.920 --> 00:38:52.997
that people got
into understanding

00:38:52.997 --> 00:38:55.330
the importance of whether or
not it's an inertial frame,

00:38:55.330 --> 00:38:59.430
was gunnery in the old days,
from naval ships and so forth.

00:38:59.430 --> 00:39:00.100
OK.

00:39:00.100 --> 00:39:01.724
So we have three laws.

00:39:01.724 --> 00:39:04.140
I want to talk a little bit
about the first and the third.

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:05.940
We're going to use
the second a lot.

00:39:05.940 --> 00:39:09.015
So the first law, most
people think of the first law

00:39:09.015 --> 00:39:12.770
as being a special case
of the second, right?

00:39:12.770 --> 00:39:15.950
It's just when there's no
forces, nothing changes.

00:39:15.950 --> 00:39:19.780
But I think the first law
is useful in its own right.

00:39:19.780 --> 00:39:22.720
And one of the reasons why
it's called the law of inertia,

00:39:22.720 --> 00:39:26.180
it's the law that
allows you to do a test

00:39:26.180 --> 00:39:27.930
to discover whether
or not you're actually

00:39:27.930 --> 00:39:30.220
in an inertial frame.

00:39:30.220 --> 00:39:31.770
Useful to be able to do that.

00:39:31.770 --> 00:39:36.372
So I'm going to
give you an example.

00:39:36.372 --> 00:39:38.330
And actually, I did want
to ask you a question.

00:39:38.330 --> 00:39:43.310
So three possible
answers to this question.

00:39:43.310 --> 00:39:49.730
An inertial frame
can-- how to pose this?

00:39:49.730 --> 00:39:54.760
If you're in an inertial
frame, can it be accelerating?

00:39:54.760 --> 00:39:59.480
If you're in an inertial
frame, can it be rotating?

00:39:59.480 --> 00:40:01.460
Or if you're in
an inertial frame,

00:40:01.460 --> 00:40:05.760
it can neither
accelerate or rotate.

00:40:05.760 --> 00:40:08.290
So which of those three
answers is the best answer

00:40:08.290 --> 00:40:11.940
for conditions to be
in an inertial frame?

00:40:11.940 --> 00:40:14.650
Non-accelerating,
non-rotating, or both?

00:40:14.650 --> 00:40:17.240
How many believe
non-accelerating?

00:40:20.270 --> 00:40:21.230
Just non-accelerating?

00:40:21.230 --> 00:40:23.080
How many believe in
just not rotating?

00:40:23.080 --> 00:40:25.130
How many believe both?

00:40:25.130 --> 00:40:26.310
Both is right.

00:40:26.310 --> 00:40:29.260
If you are in a frame which
is rotating or accelerating

00:40:29.260 --> 00:40:31.270
it's not inertial.

00:40:31.270 --> 00:40:31.770
OK.

00:40:31.770 --> 00:40:34.420
So just rotation causes
it not to be [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:34.420 --> 00:40:35.940
So let's test that.

00:40:35.940 --> 00:40:40.070
I'm going to pick
two cases quickly.

00:40:40.070 --> 00:40:44.820
Let's use this law
of inertia to set up

00:40:44.820 --> 00:40:48.350
a test to see if a couple
different frames are

00:40:48.350 --> 00:40:49.320
in fact inertial.

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:51.750
So I've got a cart here.

00:40:58.580 --> 00:41:01.430
And I'm sitting
here-- or you are.

00:41:01.430 --> 00:41:04.220
We're sitting on the cart.

00:41:04.220 --> 00:41:13.150
And this cart is accelerating.

00:41:17.210 --> 00:41:20.970
Acceleration of A
with respect to O

00:41:20.970 --> 00:41:26.470
is, I'll call it a naught I hat.

00:41:26.470 --> 00:41:29.770
This cart's accelerating in
that way, that direction,

00:41:29.770 --> 00:41:31.540
the positive I hat direction.

00:41:31.540 --> 00:41:32.410
OK.

00:41:32.410 --> 00:41:37.070
Now I'm sitting here on the
cart-- not very sensitive.

00:41:37.070 --> 00:41:41.490
And I want to test whether or
not I'm in an inertial frame.

00:41:41.490 --> 00:41:44.380
So let's pretend this cart,
I've got an air table there,

00:41:44.380 --> 00:41:45.325
frictionless table.

00:41:45.325 --> 00:41:47.330
And I've got a hockey puck.

00:41:47.330 --> 00:41:50.730
And I set it down on
the frictionless table

00:41:50.730 --> 00:41:52.960
and let it go.

00:41:52.960 --> 00:41:53.920
What happens?

00:41:53.920 --> 00:41:54.880
What do I observe?

00:41:57.327 --> 00:41:58.202
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:01.650 --> 00:42:05.660
PROFESSOR: So the puck
will accelerate, you're

00:42:05.660 --> 00:42:08.640
saying, towards me, right?

00:42:08.640 --> 00:42:10.835
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:10.835 --> 00:42:11.460
PROFESSOR: Hmm.

00:42:11.460 --> 00:42:12.600
It'll move.

00:42:12.600 --> 00:42:15.490
So she says the puck will move
towards you if you let it go.

00:42:15.490 --> 00:42:17.750
So is that an indication
of whether or not

00:42:17.750 --> 00:42:18.950
you're in an inertial frame?

00:42:21.550 --> 00:42:23.360
So the test-- this
is first law, now.

00:42:23.360 --> 00:42:25.690
So the test-- if
you're in this frame,

00:42:25.690 --> 00:42:28.940
and you want to know whether or
not this is an inertial frame,

00:42:28.940 --> 00:42:31.730
and I claim you can set
this puck out there,

00:42:31.730 --> 00:42:36.024
if you're in an inertial
frame, what should it do?

00:42:36.024 --> 00:42:36.910
Not move.

00:42:36.910 --> 00:42:39.830
If it moves, there's
something going on.

00:42:39.830 --> 00:42:41.370
Something fishy, right?

00:42:41.370 --> 00:42:42.210
OK.

00:42:42.210 --> 00:42:46.530
So the acceleration--
and we'll call

00:42:46.530 --> 00:42:51.250
the puck at B. So
the acceleration of B

00:42:51.250 --> 00:42:53.320
with respect to O-- and
there's no rotation here.

00:42:53.320 --> 00:42:56.320
So the acceleration of
B with respect to O,

00:42:56.320 --> 00:42:58.710
it can be written as
the acceleration of A

00:42:58.710 --> 00:43:02.250
with respect to O, plus
the acceleration of B

00:43:02.250 --> 00:43:11.280
with respect to A.

00:43:11.280 --> 00:43:14.990
Now this is O here.

00:43:14.990 --> 00:43:16.547
This is an inertial frame.

00:43:19.530 --> 00:43:22.390
And if it's an inertial
frame, and there

00:43:22.390 --> 00:43:26.670
are no forces in the x
direction acting on this puck,

00:43:26.670 --> 00:43:29.260
then I'm going to say that the
sum of the forces on that puck

00:43:29.260 --> 00:43:32.100
equal zero.

00:43:32.100 --> 00:43:35.000
And therefore, what can I
say about the acceleration

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.440
of the puck?

00:43:37.440 --> 00:43:41.589
What's the acceleration of
the puck as seen from O?

00:43:41.589 --> 00:43:42.380
It's gotta be zero.

00:43:42.380 --> 00:43:47.390
If no forces-- so the summation
of the forces with respect

00:43:47.390 --> 00:43:51.190
to this O frame in
the x direction,

00:43:51.190 --> 00:43:54.830
if there's zero, that
implies the acceleration of B

00:43:54.830 --> 00:43:56.770
with respect to O
is got to be zero.

00:44:01.730 --> 00:44:06.730
Knowing that, I can now solve
for the acceleration of B

00:44:06.730 --> 00:44:09.610
with respect to A.
And that's going

00:44:09.610 --> 00:44:13.315
to be minus the acceleration
of A with respect to O.

00:44:13.315 --> 00:44:18.425
And that's minus a naught I hat.

00:44:23.070 --> 00:44:27.420
So you are correct in
saying that it moves.

00:44:27.420 --> 00:44:31.390
But it actually accelerates.

00:44:31.390 --> 00:44:35.354
From your point of view, what
you see sitting there in A,

00:44:35.354 --> 00:44:36.895
you were going to
see this accelerate

00:44:36.895 --> 00:44:38.310
in the opposite direction.

00:44:38.310 --> 00:44:40.080
And that's a dead
giveaway that you're not

00:44:40.080 --> 00:44:41.890
in an inertial frame.

00:44:41.890 --> 00:44:42.390
OK.

00:44:50.380 --> 00:44:53.910
Come on.

00:44:53.910 --> 00:44:55.270
OK.

00:44:55.270 --> 00:44:56.460
So a little harder problem.

00:45:05.550 --> 00:45:08.863
Now we've got our
merry-go-round.

00:45:08.863 --> 00:45:10.220
OK.

00:45:10.220 --> 00:45:11.220
And it's fixed.

00:45:11.220 --> 00:45:12.395
Not on the train.

00:45:12.395 --> 00:45:14.220
It's just sitting here.

00:45:14.220 --> 00:45:17.160
But it can spin.

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:20.340
And you're sitting
at A. So you're

00:45:20.340 --> 00:45:24.040
up above this merry-go-round
looking down on it.

00:45:24.040 --> 00:45:25.937
And it's rotating.

00:45:25.937 --> 00:45:27.520
Out there you're in
an inertial frame.

00:45:27.520 --> 00:45:29.728
But now you come over to
here, and you sit right here

00:45:29.728 --> 00:45:31.840
at the center.

00:45:31.840 --> 00:45:33.390
And if you're right
at the center,

00:45:33.390 --> 00:45:36.200
you might not actually
feel a thing, right?

00:45:36.200 --> 00:45:37.820
And there's no windows.

00:45:37.820 --> 00:45:43.330
So this could be a spaceship
out there, slowly rolling over.

00:45:43.330 --> 00:45:46.450
So you're sitting
inside of this system,

00:45:46.450 --> 00:45:49.200
no windows, right at the
