Same point right here.

00:58:03.360 --> 00:58:07.090
But now you see it as
being going off like that.

00:58:07.090 --> 00:58:10.040
To you, it's hooking off
in the direction opposite

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:11.800
to the direction of rotation.

00:58:11.800 --> 00:58:14.630
So the young man up there
who described that early on

00:58:14.630 --> 00:58:16.910
was exactly right.

00:58:16.910 --> 00:58:21.177
So from your point of view,
it goes mrrmm, like that.

00:58:21.177 --> 00:58:22.760
And then if you go
all the way around,

00:58:22.760 --> 00:58:23.880
it'll appear to come back.

00:58:23.880 --> 00:58:27.370
It'll be further
away, but you'll

00:58:27.370 --> 00:58:29.600
be back down to the point
where you see it released.

00:58:29.600 --> 00:58:34.440
So it'll look like it goes
from your point of view.

00:58:34.440 --> 00:58:35.970
OK.

00:58:35.970 --> 00:58:36.530
Good one.

00:58:44.410 --> 00:58:47.220
OK, we've got a
few minutes left.

00:58:47.220 --> 00:58:50.507
I want to do something really
important with the third law.

00:58:50.507 --> 00:58:52.340
So the first law's
actually pretty important

00:58:52.340 --> 00:58:54.545
and very handy.

00:58:54.545 --> 00:58:56.670
The second law, we're going
to make lots of use of.

00:58:56.670 --> 00:58:59.010
So I want to talk a minute
about the third law.

00:58:59.010 --> 00:59:08.090
The third law is responsible
for a law that we use,

00:59:08.090 --> 00:59:10.650
or an application that
we use all the time.

00:59:10.650 --> 00:59:13.500
And let's see how
this works out.

00:59:13.500 --> 00:59:15.070
So Newton's third
law is the one that

00:59:15.070 --> 00:59:17.530
says F 21 is equal to F 12.

00:59:21.250 --> 00:59:24.170
So we have these two particles.

00:59:24.170 --> 00:59:31.040
And I called them 2 and 1.

00:59:31.040 --> 00:59:36.780
And I'll give this
one mass 1, mass 2.

00:59:36.780 --> 00:59:39.650
And I'm going to say
second law tells me

00:59:39.650 --> 00:59:50.250
that the sum of the forces,
vectors, external forces, on 2

00:59:50.250 --> 00:59:54.130
is-- and this one,
let's say it has things,

00:59:54.130 --> 00:59:55.830
active forces acting on it.

00:59:55.830 --> 00:59:57.940
F i's.

00:59:57.940 --> 01:00:02.120
And it has this little f 21.

01:00:02.120 --> 01:00:09.730
So the forces here are
the external forces

01:00:09.730 --> 01:00:21.220
that are vectors, plus f,
[? some ?] of the forces on 2.

01:00:21.220 --> 01:00:23.290
So forces on 2 due to 1.

01:00:23.290 --> 01:00:26.146
That's external influence
of the other particle.

01:00:26.146 --> 01:00:27.930
OK?

01:00:27.930 --> 01:00:40.520
And this had better be equal
to m 2 a 2, I'll call it.

01:00:40.520 --> 01:00:44.100
And with respect to some
fixed, some inertial frame.

01:00:44.100 --> 01:00:49.210
So the sum of all these external
forces on that particle 2

01:00:49.210 --> 01:00:51.460
had better be equal to the
mass times the acceleration

01:00:51.460 --> 01:00:53.120
of particle 2.

01:00:53.120 --> 01:00:56.370
And the same thing can
be said about particle 1.

01:00:56.370 --> 01:00:58.260
So I've really
confused things here.

01:00:58.260 --> 01:01:00.910
There's 2, and there's 1.

01:01:00.910 --> 01:01:01.610
Boy.

01:01:01.610 --> 01:01:02.720
OK.

01:01:02.720 --> 01:01:05.210
Guys, help keep me honest here.

01:01:05.210 --> 01:01:08.300
So now that we can say
the sum of the forces on 1

01:01:08.300 --> 01:01:16.560
is equal to these external
applied forces, plus f 12--

01:01:16.560 --> 01:01:19.610
the force caused
by the other body.

01:01:19.610 --> 01:01:23.387
And those had better
equal to m 1 a 1/0.

01:01:23.387 --> 01:01:23.886
OK.

01:01:27.540 --> 01:01:37.970
And these are also equal to the
time derivative of m 2 v 2/0.

01:01:37.970 --> 01:01:40.990
That's the momentum, the time
derivative of the momentum.

01:01:40.990 --> 01:01:43.930
It's fixed mass, so it's
just the derivative velocity

01:01:43.930 --> 01:01:44.900
gives the acceleration.

01:01:44.900 --> 01:01:47.320
So these are clearly
the same formula.

01:01:47.320 --> 01:01:53.880
And this is a time derivative
of m 1 v 1 with respect to O dt.

01:01:53.880 --> 01:02:00.370
And we call that
P 2 dot, P 1 dot.

01:02:00.370 --> 01:02:02.681
So these are statements
that are applying second law

01:02:02.681 --> 01:02:03.805
to each of these particles.

01:02:08.280 --> 01:02:19.310
So if I want to compute the
total momentum of the system.

01:02:19.310 --> 01:02:23.300
So the linear momentum, the
total momentum of the system

01:02:23.300 --> 01:02:27.070
is going to be P 1 plus P 2.

01:02:27.070 --> 01:02:28.990
They're vectors.

01:02:28.990 --> 01:02:32.640
And I want to take
the time derivative

01:02:32.640 --> 01:02:34.510
of that total momentum.

01:02:38.810 --> 01:02:40.950
Just the time
derivative of a sum

01:02:40.950 --> 01:02:42.460
is the sum of the
time derivatives.

01:02:42.460 --> 01:02:46.225
And so I get a P 1
dot plus a P 2 dot.

01:02:49.230 --> 01:02:50.600
But I know what those are.

01:02:50.600 --> 01:02:52.175
I have expressions for them.

01:02:55.920 --> 01:03:04.750
So this is F 1 external
forces plus f 12

01:03:04.750 --> 01:03:14.790
plus the F 2 external
forces plus f 21.

01:03:14.790 --> 01:03:15.700
These two things.

01:03:15.700 --> 01:03:18.570
This one plus this
one, basically,

01:03:18.570 --> 01:03:23.410
is the sum of the two time
derivatives of the momentum.

01:03:23.410 --> 01:03:26.380
But what's the sum of
this term and that term?

01:03:26.380 --> 01:03:27.054
AUDIENCE: Zero.

01:03:27.054 --> 01:03:27.720
PROFESSOR: Zero.

01:03:31.560 --> 01:03:35.260
And that then allows
you to say that this

01:03:35.260 --> 01:03:45.890
is the sum of the external
forces on a system is

01:03:45.890 --> 01:03:49.272
equal to the time rate of
change of the linear momentum

01:03:49.272 --> 01:03:49.855
of the system.

01:03:55.670 --> 01:03:56.670
OK.

01:03:56.670 --> 01:04:00.180
And that's basically
this statement.

01:04:00.180 --> 01:04:03.160
And it has nothing to
do with internal forces.

01:04:08.860 --> 01:04:13.050
And this allows you
to say that the time

01:04:13.050 --> 01:04:16.930
rate of change of the linear
momentum of a rigid body,

01:04:16.930 --> 01:04:19.720
for example.

01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:22.885
So a rigid body is
made up of a whole mess

01:04:22.885 --> 01:04:25.430
of different particles.

01:04:25.430 --> 01:04:28.100
You could separate this into a
whole bunch of little chunks,

01:04:28.100 --> 01:04:33.560
and treat each one of them as a
particle which has connection,

01:04:33.560 --> 01:04:36.210
has forces with
particles next to it.

01:04:36.210 --> 01:04:39.140
And all those internal
forces-- so these

01:04:39.140 --> 01:04:43.390
are the internal forces--
all of those internal forces

01:04:43.390 --> 01:04:45.830
are equal and
opposite and cancel.

01:04:45.830 --> 01:04:47.780
So it's really
the third law that

01:04:47.780 --> 01:04:51.300
allows you to say if you
have a system of particles

01:04:51.300 --> 01:04:54.690
that the time rate of
change of the total momentum

01:04:54.690 --> 01:04:58.050
of the system is zero if there's
no external forces acting

01:04:58.050 --> 01:04:58.550
on it.

01:04:58.550 --> 01:05:01.510
And that's where you get the
conservation of momentum--

01:05:01.510 --> 01:05:04.692
the law of conservation
of momentum.

01:05:04.692 --> 01:05:05.600
OK.

01:05:05.600 --> 01:05:07.580
That's a consequence
of the third law.

01:05:15.460 --> 01:05:15.960
OK.

01:05:51.590 --> 01:05:55.950
So you have a homework problem
that has just about this.

01:05:55.950 --> 01:05:58.840
You have a bunch of particles.

01:05:58.840 --> 01:06:01.230
m 1.

01:06:01.230 --> 01:06:03.128
m i.

01:06:03.128 --> 01:06:10.830
r 1 with respect to O.
r i with respect to O.

01:06:10.830 --> 01:06:13.779
And you have all these
particles out there.

01:06:13.779 --> 01:06:15.320
And I want to find
the center of mass

01:06:15.320 --> 01:06:16.445
of this group of particles.

01:06:20.170 --> 01:06:22.340
So the center of
mass is a vector.

01:06:22.340 --> 01:06:24.900
And let's just say it's here.

01:06:24.900 --> 01:06:31.000
So I'm looking for r
G with respect to O.

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:32.910
So it's a quantity
that I defined--

01:06:32.910 --> 01:06:40.566
r G with respect to O-- times
the summation of the m i's.

01:06:40.566 --> 01:06:44.560
So I'm postulating there's
a place out there that if I

01:06:44.560 --> 01:06:49.120
multiply it by the sum of the
m i's, I get the same answer

01:06:49.120 --> 01:06:54.520
as if I summed the m i r i/O's.

01:06:57.190 --> 01:06:59.930
And I'm going to define
the center of mass

01:06:59.930 --> 01:07:07.450
as r G with respect to O is
the summation of each particle

01:07:07.450 --> 01:07:12.140
times its position
vector divided

01:07:12.140 --> 01:07:13.920
by the sum of the
masses, which is just

01:07:13.920 --> 01:07:16.398
the total mass of the system.

01:07:16.398 --> 01:07:17.210
OK?

01:07:17.210 --> 01:07:19.910
And that's a definition
of center of mass.

01:07:19.910 --> 01:07:21.490
And this is a vector.

01:07:21.490 --> 01:07:23.470
And these are vectors.

01:07:23.470 --> 01:07:24.020
OK?

01:07:24.020 --> 01:07:26.380
So that's all there is
to the center of mass.

01:07:26.380 --> 01:07:45.240
And if I take a time
derivative of r G/O,

01:07:45.240 --> 01:07:52.025
then it's equal to the summation
of the m i times the r i/O's.

01:07:52.025 --> 01:07:53.650
But they're timed
derivatives-- and I'm

01:07:53.650 --> 01:07:55.608
going to put a dot right
there, so I don't have

01:07:55.608 --> 01:07:59.010
to write out d by dt-- over MT.

01:07:59.010 --> 01:08:05.800
But that's just the summation of
the individual momenta of each

01:08:05.800 --> 01:08:07.470
of the particles over MT.

01:08:11.760 --> 01:08:14.235
Very handy little formula.

01:08:16.810 --> 01:08:20.600
And if I take another
time derivative,

01:08:20.600 --> 01:08:25.729
so I get an r G/O
double dot, then it's

01:08:25.729 --> 01:08:32.029
just the summation of
the time derivatives

01:08:32.029 --> 01:08:35.160
of the individual
momenta again over this.

01:08:35.160 --> 01:08:36.189
So this is a statement.

01:08:36.189 --> 01:08:37.569
We move this to the other side.

01:08:37.569 --> 01:08:44.720
M T r G/O double dot
equals the summation

01:08:44.720 --> 01:08:49.010
of the timed derivatives
of the individual momenta.

01:08:49.010 --> 01:08:53.520
And that's the total
momentum of the system

01:08:53.520 --> 01:08:55.189
times its timed derivative.

01:08:55.189 --> 01:09:02.420
So just from third
law, you can come up

01:09:02.420 --> 01:09:06.740
with all of the linear
momentum formulas.

01:09:06.740 --> 01:09:09.229
This is a statement
for rigid body.

01:09:09.229 --> 01:09:13.399
The mass times the acceleration
of the center of mass.

01:09:13.399 --> 01:09:16.899
The total mass of a rigid
body times the acceleration

01:09:16.899 --> 01:09:20.069
of the center of mass
is equal to the time

01:09:20.069 --> 01:09:23.481
rate of change of the total
momentum of that object.

01:09:23.481 --> 01:09:24.439
Very important formula.

01:09:24.439 --> 01:09:26.020
You've used it a lot, right?

01:09:26.020 --> 01:09:28.990
So I'll tell you a quick story,
and then we'll knock off.

01:09:28.990 --> 01:09:33.270
So two, three years ago,
we have doctoral exams

01:09:33.270 --> 01:09:34.899
in mechanical engineering.

01:09:34.899 --> 01:09:37.479
And in the dynamics oral
exam, we had eight students

01:09:37.479 --> 01:09:39.229
a few years ago.

01:09:39.229 --> 01:09:42.120
And they were asked to find the
center of mass of an object.

01:09:42.120 --> 01:09:44.910
It was just a step
in a harder problem.

01:09:44.910 --> 01:09:46.810
And seven out of
the eight students

01:09:46.810 --> 01:09:49.260
could not remember
the definition

01:09:49.260 --> 01:09:50.840
of the center of mass.

01:09:50.840 --> 01:09:54.037
Now they could do Lagrange
equations and nasty dynamics

01:09:54.037 --> 01:09:55.620
problems, but they'd
kind of forgotten

01:09:55.620 --> 01:09:58.290
some of these really,
really basic things.

01:09:58.290 --> 01:10:01.910
So I have one demo
to show you, just

01:10:01.910 --> 01:10:03.520
to illustrate center of mass.

01:10:03.520 --> 01:10:08.490
So center of mass, we
know how to calculate it.

01:10:08.490 --> 01:10:10.570
And this is a rod.

01:10:10.570 --> 01:10:13.657
How can I simply find the
center of mass of this thing?

01:10:13.657 --> 01:10:14.790
AUDIENCE: Balance it.

01:10:14.790 --> 01:10:16.861
PROFESSOR: Balance it.

01:10:16.861 --> 01:10:17.360
OK.

01:10:17.360 --> 01:10:19.980
Young lady here says
move my fingers.

01:10:19.980 --> 01:10:22.210
Where do you think
the center of mass is?

01:10:22.210 --> 01:10:23.130
Right in the middle.

01:10:23.130 --> 01:10:23.410
OK.

01:10:23.410 --> 01:10:23.993
Let's find it.

01:10:29.780 --> 01:10:31.330
Should this work, by the way?

01:10:31.330 --> 01:10:32.330
You ever done this?

01:10:35.762 --> 01:10:37.345
All right, the center
of mass, I ought

01:10:37.345 --> 01:10:39.435
to be able to just about
balance this thing there.

01:10:39.435 --> 01:10:41.060
So the center of mass
is in the middle.

01:10:41.060 --> 01:10:41.960
That's because I cheated.

01:10:41.960 --> 01:10:43.418
I put a piece of
steel in this end.

01:10:43.418 --> 01:10:44.709
OK?

01:10:44.709 --> 01:10:46.010
All right.

01:10:46.010 --> 01:10:49.729
But indeed, you might figure out
why is it that I can actually

01:10:49.729 --> 01:10:50.770
do this and make it work.

01:10:50.770 --> 01:10:51.530
You can do it with a broomstick.

01:10:51.530 --> 01:10:53.340
You can do it with any object.

01:10:53.340 --> 01:10:56.330
The key is it'll work so long
as the friction coefficients are

01:10:56.330 --> 01:10:58.550
the same on both fingers.

01:10:58.550 --> 01:11:01.050
It's really easy to find
center of mass that way.

01:11:01.050 --> 01:11:03.230
So this got a little
steel weight in the end.

01:11:03.230 --> 01:11:03.730
OK.

01:11:03.730 --> 01:11:05.220
We're done for today.

01:11:05.220 --> 01:11:09.150
And see you on Thursday.

